props.propertyComment:
This Boolean attribute specifies that the button should have input focus when the page loads.
 Only one element in a document can have this attribute.

An array of the nested HTML elements.
 > If there is an element in the children property the text is not rendered.
This Boolean attribute prevents the user from interacting with the button: it cannot be pressed or focused.

Global attributes are attributes common to all HTML elements;
 they can be used on all elements, though they may have no effect on some elements.

An integer attribute indicating if the element can take input focus (is focusable),
 if it should participate to sequential keyboard navigation, and if so, at what position.

Contains a text representing advisory information related to the element it belongs to.
 Such information can typically, but not necessarily, be presented to the user as a tooltip.
The name of the button, submitted as a pair with the button’s value as part of the form data.

Text content value.
 > If there is an element in the children property the text is not rendered.

The default behavior of the button. Possible values are:
 * submit: The button submits the form data to the server. This is the default if the attribute is not specified for buttons associated with a <form>, or if the attribute is an empty or invalid value.
 * button: The button has no default behavior, and does nothing when pressed by default. It can have client-side scripts listen to the element's events, which are triggered when the events occur.

Defines the value associated with the button’s name when it’s submitted with the form data.
 This value is passed to the server in params when the form is submitted.
